##Conclusion
Malaria is a serious disease that affects millions of people worldwide, especially in developing countries. Early and accurate detection is important to provide proper treatment and reduce the risk of severe health complications. Traditionally, malaria is detected by examining blood smear images under a microscope, which requires skilled medical experts and takes time.
In this project, deep learning techniques were used to detect malaria from microscopic images of blood cells. A dataset containing images of parasitized (infected) and uninfected red blood cells was collected and prepared for training the model. The deep learning model learns patterns and features from these images to identify whether a cell is infected or not.
The results show that deep learning can help in detecting malaria quickly and accurately. Such automated systems can assist doctors and reduce the workload in medical laboratories. This technology can be very useful in rural and remote areas where medical resources are limited.
